<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-peach-tips">Peach Tips</h2>



<p>The only &ldquo;hard&rdquo; part about this recipe is finding great peaches. Wait to make it until you can find an abundance of ripe or nearly-ripe fresh peaches. </p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-peach-selection-and-care">Peach selection and care</h3>



<p><strong>Look for medium-to-large peaches that are fragrant, unblemished and yield slightly to a gentle squeeze.</strong> Treat them gently so they don&rsquo;t bruise. </p>



<p><strong>If your peaches aren&rsquo;t ripe yet,</strong> store them at room temperature until they are (you can speed their ripening by storing them in a paper bag, but give each peach some space so they don&rsquo;t mold). </p>



<p><strong>If your peaches are ripe already</strong> and you can&rsquo;t bake the cobbler right away, store them in the refrigerator to keep them good for another day or two.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-how-to-peel-peaches">How to peel peaches</h3>



<p><strong>You don&rsquo;t have to peel the peaches</strong> if you&rsquo;re not bothered by some texture in your dessert (I didn&rsquo;t mind it, but my husband did). </p>



<p><strong>If you want to peel the peaches,</strong> lightly score an &ldquo;x&rdquo; about two inches wide at the base of each peach, gently dunk them into a big pot of boiling water for 30 seconds to 1 minute, then transfer them to an ice bath. Peel off the skin starting from the cuts on the bottom, and it will come off easily in strips.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-how-to-cut-your-peaches">How to cut your peaches</h3>



<p><strong>Slice your peaches into one-inch chunks</strong> instead of long strips. They offer perfect bites and don&rsquo;t disappear to mush. This is a handy tip I picked up from <a href="https://sallysbakingaddiction.com/fresh-peach-cobbler/">Sally</a>&mdash;thanks Sally! </p>



